What is actually happening

Those 404s are mostly for framework/static resource requests, such as:
	•	/ips/css/ipsStyles_otp.css
	•	/ips/js/ipsCommon.js
	•	/ips/js/ips_gtm.js
	•	/IPSWeb/javax.faces.resource/jsf.js.xhtml
	•	/.../popupPanel.css.xhtml
	•	/.../status.js.xhtml
	•	/.../popupPanel.js.xhtml
	•	/.../popupPanelBorders.js.xhtml
	•	/.../popupPanelSizer.js.xhtml
	•	/.../buttonBackgroundImage.png.xhtml
	•	/.../buttonHoverBackgroundImage.png.xhtml

Your filter change likely introduced this because of one important regression:

Regression

In the newer code, nv.setBooleanValue(true) is being set for any query string that passes validation.

Then doFilter() does:

if (redirect) {
    httpResponse.sendRedirect(httpRequest.getRequestURL().toString());
}

That redirect drops the query string.

For framework resource requests, those query params are often required.
So the browser requests something like:

.../popupPanel.css.xhtml?db=eAHj...

but your redirect turns it into:

.../popupPanel.css.xhtml

and that becomes 404.

So the real fix is:
	1.	Do not redirect every valid query-string request
	2.	Skip XSS validation for framework/static resource requests

⸻

Correct fix

1) Only set redirect=true for legacy do / cmd case

Do not set redirect just because a query string exists.

2) Bypass framework/static resource requests entirely

Use a helper that covers the full set from your screenshot so you stop doing this iteratively.

